  <!-- ═══ DRY LAB ═══ -->
  <section class="section" id="drylab" aria-labelledby="drylab-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="eyebrow">Computational methods</p>
        <h2 id="drylab-heading">Dry lab: structural prediction and docking</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-dl1">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">DL-1</div>
          <div>
            <h3>AlphaFold3 structure prediction</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--confirmed">Confirmed</span>
              <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-structure`} class="method-link">View results →</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            Full-length CxnA protein structure was predicted using
            <strong>AlphaFold3</strong> (Google DeepMind, 2024) via the publicly accessible
            AlphaFold Server. Separate predictions were run for the GH10/Cex catalytic domain
            and the GH1-fold domain to obtain higher-resolution models of each active site.
          </p>
          <h4>Parameters</h4>
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li><strong>Input:</strong> CxnA amino acid sequence (full-length; domain boundaries as per Duedu &amp; French 2016)</li>
            <li><strong>Model version:</strong> AlphaFold3 (server, accessed 2025)</li>
            <li><strong>Templates:</strong> Used where available (default server settings)</li>
            <li><strong>Number of recycles:</strong> Default (3)</li>
            <li><strong>Output:</strong> mmCIF structure files, pLDDT confidence scores, PAE (Predicted Aligned Error) matrix</li>
          </ul>
          <h4>Output quality assessment</h4>
          <p>
            pLDDT scores above 90 in the catalytic core of both GH10 and GH1 domains indicate
            high per-residue confidence. Regions connecting domains (linker segments) showed
            lower pLDDT (60–75), consistent with expected flexibility.
            PAE plots confirmed low inter-domain error for active-site residues.
          </p>
          <details class="expand mt-4">
            <summary>Note on AlphaFold3 vs AlphaFold2 for this application</summary>
            <div class="expand-body">
              <p>
                AlphaFold3 was selected over AlphaFold2 for its improved modelling of
                ligand-binding pockets and multi-chain assemblies. For the purposes of
                structure validation and docking grid preparation, the single-chain prediction
                is sufficient. AlphaFold3 predictions should be treated as computational
                models, not experimental structures — hence the RMSD validation against 1FHD
                (Method DL-2) as a critical quality check before proceeding to docking.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-dl2">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">DL-2</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Structural validation: RMSD against 1FHD crystal structure</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--confirmed">Confirmed</span>
              <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-structure`} class="method-link">View results →</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            To assess the accuracy of the AlphaFold3 GH10/Cex model, it was structurally
            superimposed against the published X-ray crystal structure of the Cex exoglucanase
            from <em>Cellulomonas fimi</em> (PDB: <code>1FHD</code>, Notenboom et al., 1998).
          </p>
          <h4>Alignment procedure</h4>
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li><strong>Tool:</strong> PyMOL v2.5 (Schrödinger) — <code>align</code> command with default parameters</li>
            <li><strong>Alignment basis:</strong> Cα atoms of the GH10 catalytic domain, residues <span class="badge badge--pending">range pending</span></li>
            <li><strong>Outlier removal:</strong> Standard PyMOL iterative rejection (5 cycles, 2σ cutoff)</li>
            <li><strong>Key result:</strong> RMSD = <strong>0.293 Å</strong> over aligned Cα atoms</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="callout">
            <p class="callout-title">Interpretation</p>
            <p>
              An RMSD of 0.293 Å is well within the range expected for near-identical
              structures (typically &lt;1.0 Å for the same protein fold). This result gives
              high confidence that the AlphaFold3 model accurately represents the GH10/Cex
              active-site geometry and that downstream docking predictions are structurally
              grounded. See <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-structure`}>Results</a> for the
              full overlay figure and per-residue deviation plot.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-dl3">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">DL-3</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Molecular docking: Autodock Vina</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--confirmed">Confirmed</span>
              <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-docking`} class="method-link">View results →</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            Cellobiose was docked into both the GH10/Cex and GH1-fold active sites using
            <strong>Autodock Vina 1.2</strong>. Xylobiose was also docked into GH10
            as a comparative substrate (see caveat below).
          </p>
          <h4>Protocol</h4>
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li><strong>Receptor preparation:</strong> AlphaFold3 mmCIF → PDB format. Hydrogens added using AutoDockTools 1.5.7. Water molecules removed. Gasteiger charges assigned.</li>
            <li><strong>Ligand preparation:</strong> Cellobiose SMILES retrieved from PubChem (CID 10712). 3D conformer generated using Open Babel. Torsion bonds set free.</li>
            <li><strong>Docking grid:</strong> Centered on the catalytic glutamates (GLU127/GLU233 for GH10; GLU350/GLU404 for GH1). Grid box: 20 × 20 × 20 Å, spacing 0.375 Å.</li>
            <li><strong>Exhaustiveness:</strong> 32 (increased from default 8 for greater sampling)</li>
            <li><strong>Number of poses:</strong> 20 retained per run</li>
            <li><strong>Replicate runs:</strong> 3 per target to assess pose reproducibility</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="callout callout--warn mt-4">
            <p class="callout-title">Critical caveat: absolute docking scores</p>
            <p>
              Autodock Vina binding free energy scores (kcal/mol) are semi-empirical
              estimates and <strong>systematically overestimate true binding affinity</strong>
              in many cases. They are reliable for rank-ordering poses of the same ligand
              within the same receptor (relative comparison), but absolute scores should not
              be taken as accurate predictions of experimental ΔG.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-4">
              <strong>Worked example of this limitation:</strong> Docking of xylobiose into
              GH10 yields a Vina score <span class="badge badge--pending">value pending</span> kcal/mol more favourable than cellobiose, despite
              cellobiose being the natural substrate. This discrepancy illustrates that
              improved docking scores do not automatically indicate biologically superior
              substrates, and that experimental validation is always required.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-dl4">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">DL-4</div>
          <div>
            <h3>PLIP &amp; PoseView: interaction analysis</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--confirmed">Confirmed</span>
              <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-plip`} class="method-link">View results →</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            Protein–ligand interactions for the top-ranked docking poses were analysed using
            <strong>PLIP</strong> (Protein–Ligand Interaction Profiler, Adasme et al., 2021)
            and visualised using <strong>PoseView</strong> (BioSolveIT).
          </p>
          <h4>Interactions characterised</h4>
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li>Hydrogen bonds (donor–acceptor pairs, distances, angles)</li>
            <li>Hydrophobic contacts (Cβ–ligand distances ≤ 4.0 Å)</li>
            <li>Stacking interactions (π–π, T-shaped)</li>
            <li>Salt bridges (charge–charge)</li>
          </ul>
          <h4>Key residues identified</h4>
          <table class="data-table mt-4">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Domain</th>
                <th>Residue</th>
                <th>Role</th>
                <th>Interaction type</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>GH10</td><td class="mono">GLU127</td><td>Catalytic nucleophile</td><td>H-bond (donor to ligand O3)</td></tr>
              <tr><td>GH10</td><td class="mono">GLU233</td><td>Acid/base catalyst</td><td>H-bond (acceptor from ligand O1)</td></tr>
              <tr><td>GH1</td><td class="mono">GLU350</td><td>Candidate nucleophile</td><td>H-bond (tentative)</td></tr>
              <tr><td>GH1</td><td class="mono">GLU404</td><td>Candidate acid/base</td><td>H-bond (tentative)</td></tr>
              <tr><td>GH1</td><td class="mono">GLN87</td><td>Steric barrier</td><td>Steric clash with cellobiose</td></tr>
              <tr><td>GH1</td><td class="mono">TRP281</td><td>Steric barrier</td><td>Hydrophobic obstruction</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <p class="mt-4" style="font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--c-text-muted)">
            Full PLIP output, PoseView 2D diagrams, and pose cluster analysis:
            <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-plip`}>Results → PLIP Analysis</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-dl5">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">DL-5</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Pose convergence analysis</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--confirmed">Confirmed</span>
              <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-convergence`} class="method-link">View results →</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            To assess docking reliability, the 20 retained poses per target were clustered
            by RMSD (cutoff: 2.0 Å) to evaluate convergence. High convergence
            (poses clustering tightly) indicates that the docking algorithm consistently
            identifies the same binding geometry. Pose scatter indicates ambiguity.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-4">
            <strong>GH10:</strong> Tight clustering of poses (see Results for RMSD distribution histogram).
            This supports high confidence in the predicted binding geometry for downstream PLIP analysis.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-4">
            <strong>GH1:</strong> Poses show greater scatter across the domain surface.
            This is flagged as requiring further investigation — it may indicate that the
            GH1-fold does not possess a well-defined cellobiose-binding pocket in the current
            structural model, consistent with the absence of GH1-type activity in wild-type CxnA.
            <strong>This result is not overclaimed.</strong> The scatter is noted as an open
            question that wet-lab results will need to address.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ WET LAB ═══ -->
  <section class="section section--alt" id="wetlab" aria-labelledby="wetlab-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="eyebrow">Molecular biology</p>
        <h2 id="wetlab-heading">Wet lab: cloning, mutagenesis, selection, and screening</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-wl1">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">WL-1</div>
          <div>
            <h3>CxnA gene acquisition and expression vector cloning</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--progress">In Progress</span>
              <a href={`${b}/results#wetlab-cloning`} class="method-link">Results (pending) →</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <h4>Gene acquisition</h4>
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li><strong>Source:</strong> CxnA coding sequence from <em>Cellulomonas fimi</em> (GenBank accession per Duedu &amp; French 2016)</li>
            <li><strong>Synthesis/source:</strong> <span class="badge badge--pending">Pending</span> <span class="pending-hint">gene synthesis provider / isolation method</span></li>
            <li><strong>Codon optimisation:</strong> <span class="badge badge--pending">Pending</span> <span class="pending-hint">E. coli K-12 optimisation if applicable</span></li>
          </ul>
          <h4>Expression vector</h4>
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li><strong>Vector:</strong> <span class="badge badge--pending">Pending</span> <span class="pending-hint">pET / pBAD / other</span></li>
            <li><strong>Promoter:</strong> <span class="badge badge--pending">Pending</span> <span class="pending-hint">T7 / araBAD / other</span></li>
            <li><strong>Affinity tag:</strong> <span class="badge badge--pending">Pending</span> <span class="pending-hint">His₆ / Strep / none</span></li>
            <li><strong>Restriction sites:</strong> <span class="badge badge--pending">Pending</span> <span class="pending-hint">e.g. NdeI/XhoI</span></li>
            <li><strong>Host strain:</strong> <em>E. coli</em> <span class="badge badge--pending">Pending</span> <span class="pending-hint">BL21(DE3) / DH5α / other</span></li>
          </ul>
          <h4>Cloning procedure</h4>
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li>Restriction digestion of insert and vector with <span class="badge badge--pending">enzymes pending</span></li>
            <li>Gel purification of digestion products</li>
            <li>Ligation (T4 DNA Ligase, NEB, 16°C overnight)</li>
            <li>Transformation into <em>E. coli</em> DH5α by heat shock</li>
            <li>Colony PCR screening with T7 primers to confirm insert</li>
            <li>Sanger sequencing of 3–5 positive clones to verify correct sequence</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="callout callout--warn mt-4">
            <p class="callout-title">Lab notebook cross-reference</p>
            <p>
              All gel images, transformation efficiencies, and sequencing results for cloning
              are recorded in the lab notebook (notebook entries to be linked here in Phase 2 of the site).
              Includes documentation of a failed ligation attempt <span class="badge badge--pending">date TBC</span> and the
              protocol modification that resolved it.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-wl2">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">WL-2</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Error-prone PCR (epPCR) mutagenesis library generation</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--progress">In Progress</span>
              <a href={`${b}/results#wetlab-eppcr`} class="method-link">Results (pending) →</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            Error-prone PCR introduces random nucleotide substitutions at a controlled rate
            across the target gene. We use the Mn²⁺-dNTP imbalance method to bias
            toward a target mutation rate of approximately 1–3 amino acid changes per gene,
            which empirically maximises the probability of finding beneficial single-site
            and double-site mutations without excessive fitness loss from multiple deleterious changes.
          </p>
          <h4>epPCR protocol</h4>
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li><strong>Polymerase:</strong> Taq (no proofreading), 5 U/reaction</li>
            <li><strong>Buffer:</strong> Standard Taq buffer + 0.5 mM MnCl₂</li>
            <li><strong>dNTP imbalance:</strong> 200 µM dATP, 200 µM dGTP, 1 mM dCTP, 1 mM dTTP</li>
            <li><strong>Template:</strong> 1 ng plasmid carrying wild-type CxnA</li>
            <li><strong>Primers:</strong> Flanking the target region with 20-mer tails matching vector sequence</li>
            <li><strong>Cycles:</strong> 35 cycles (94°C 30s / 55°C 30s / 72°C 90s)</li>
            <li><strong>Library size target:</strong> ≥10³ unique colonies</li>
          </ul>
          <h4>Library validation</h4>
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li>10 random colonies sequenced to determine empirical mutation rate</li>
            <li>Acceptance criterion: average 1–4 bp substitutions per gene</li>
            <li>Libraries with &gt;6 bp average substitutions are discarded and repeated</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="callout mt-4">
            <p class="callout-title">Project-specific targeting (informed by DL-3/DL-4)</p>
            <p>
              For Project A, epPCR is prioritised over the GH1-fold region (residues <span class="badge badge--pending">range pending</span>),
              informed by the docking and PLIP analysis identifying GLU350, GLU404, GLN87, and
              TRP281 as key positions. For Project B, epPCR covers the full GH10 domain.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-wl3">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">WL-3</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Library transformation and expression</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--progress">In Progress</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li><strong>Host:</strong> <em>E. coli</em> BL21(DE3) (protease-deficient, high expression)</li>
            <li><strong>Transformation method:</strong> Electroporation (2.5 kV, 25 µF, 200 Ω, 0.1 cm cuvette)</li>
            <li><strong>Recovery:</strong> SOC medium, 37°C, 1 h</li>
            <li><strong>Plating:</strong> LB + appropriate antibiotic + 1 mM IPTG (inducer)</li>
            <li><strong>Colony density target:</strong> 300–500 per 90 mm plate to allow individual screening</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-wl4">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">WL-4</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Primary selection</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--progress">In Progress</span>
              <a href={`${b}/results#wetlab-selection`} class="method-link">Results (pending) →</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <h4>Project A — cellobiose sole-carbon selection</h4>
          <p>
            Transformants are plated onto M9 minimal medium with cellobiose (10 mM) as the
            sole carbon source. Wild-type <em>E. coli</em> cannot metabolise cellobiose;
            colonies that grow have either acquired or up-regulated the ability to cleave
            cellobiose, selecting for beta-glucosidase activity (or phosphotransferase
            system import — see screening step WL-5 for discrimination).
          </p>

          <h4>Project B — CMC plate clearing</h4>
          <p>
            Transformants are plated on LB + 0.5% carboxymethylcellulose (CMC) + IPTG.
            After 24 h growth, plates are stained with Congo Red (0.1%, 15 min) and
            destained with 1 M NaCl. Clear halos around colonies indicate CMCase
            (endoglucanase) activity. Halo diameter is proportional to activity level,
            enabling direct visual screening for improved endoglucanase variants.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-wl5">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">WL-5</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Secondary screening: fluorogenic enzyme assays</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--progress">In Progress</span>
              <a href={`${b}/results#wetlab-assays`} class="method-link">Results (pending) →</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            Colonies passing primary selection are screened in liquid culture with fluorogenic
            substrates. 4-methylumbelliferyl (MU) substrates release the fluorophore
            4-methylumbelliferone (MU, excitation 360 nm, emission 450 nm) upon hydrolysis,
            enabling quantitative measurement of specific enzymatic activities.
          </p>
          <table class="data-table mt-4">
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Substrate</th><th>Abbreviation</th><th>Activity detected</th><th>Relevance</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>4-methylumbelliferyl-β-D-glucopyranoside</td>
                <td class="mono">MUG</td>
                <td>Beta-glucosidase</td>
                <td>Project A (primary screen)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>4-methylumbelliferyl-β-D-cellobioside</td>
                <td class="mono">MUC</td>
                <td>Exoglucanase / cellobiohydrolase</td>
                <td>Project B</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Carboxymethylcellulose + DNS assay</td>
                <td class="mono">CMC-DNS</td>
                <td>Endoglucanase</td>
                <td>Project B (quantitative)</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <h4 class="mt-4">Assay conditions</h4>
          <ul class="param-list">
            <li><strong>Substrate concentration:</strong> 1 mM MUG/MUC in 50 mM sodium phosphate buffer, pH 7.0</li>
            <li><strong>Enzyme source:</strong> Clarified cell lysate (sonication, 4°C, 20 min, 15,000 × g)</li>
            <li><strong>Reaction volume:</strong> 200 µL in 96-well flat-bottom plate</li>
            <li><strong>Incubation:</strong> 37°C, 60 min</li>
            <li><strong>Stop:</strong> 50 µL 1 M Na₂CO₃ (raises pH, maximises MU fluorescence)</li>
            <li><strong>Measurement:</strong> Fluorescence plate reader, Ex 360 nm / Em 450 nm</li>
            <li><strong>Controls:</strong> Wild-type CxnA (positive), empty vector (negative), substrate blank</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block" id="method-wl6">
        <div class="method-header">
          <div class="method-num">WL-6</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Hit validation and sequencing</h3>
            <div class="method-status-row">
              <span class="badge badge--pending">Pending</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            Confirmed hits from WL-5 will be validated by:
          </p>
          <ol class="param-list">
            <li>Retest of the same clone in triplicate on the same day</li>
            <li>Retest in a second independent induction experiment</li>
            <li>Plasmid isolation and Sanger sequencing to identify mutations</li>
            <li>Re-transformation into a clean BL21(DE3) background to confirm that the activity is plasmid-encoded</li>
            <li>Purification of the mutant protein by <span class="badge badge--pending">method pending</span> chromatography for specific activity determination vs WT baseline</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script>
    // Highlight active TOC entry as user scrolls
    const targets = document.querySelectorAll('[id^="method-"]');
    const links = document.querySelectorAll('.toc-pill-bar a, .toc-fixed a');
    const obs = new IntersectionObserver(entries => {
      entries.forEach(e => {
        if (e.isIntersecting) {
          links.forEach(l => l.classList.remove('toc-active'));
          links.forEach(l => { if (l.getAttribute('href') === '#' + e.target.id) l.classList.add('toc-active'); });
        }
      });
    }, { rootMargin: '-56px 0px -60% 0px', threshold: 0 });
    targets.forEach(t => obs.observe(t));
  </script>

</BaseLayout>

